body:
(Verified on v5.028, both on MacOS and RHEL)

I'm having some issues when attempting to use a variable index (ex. in a for-loop) to push into a specific queue in an array. It appears as though pushing into a specific queue additionally pushes all previous elements from other queues in the array

Minimal Reproducible Example:
```verilog
module top;
  int queues [3][$];

  initial begin
    for( int i = 0; i < 3; i = i + 1) begin
      queues[i].push_back(i);
    end
    $display("%p", queues);
    $finish();
  end
endmodule
```
I'm compiling/running the above (saved as `tmp.v`) with the commands
```bash
verilator --binary tmp.v
./obj_dir/tmp
```
My expected output is 1 element per queue in the array:
```plain
'{'{'h0} , '{'h1} , '{'h2} } 
```
However, the actual output I'm getting is
```plain
'{'{'h0} , '{'h0, 'h1} , '{'h0, 'h1, 'h2} } 
```

The reason for "variable index" is because doing the following achieves the expected output:
```verilog
module top;
  int queues [3][$];

  initial begin
    queues[0].push_back(0);
    queues[1].push_back(1);
    queues[2].push_back(2);
    $display("%p", queues);
    $finish();
  end
endmodule
```

Is there something I'm doing wrong, or could contribute to a fix? Thanks in advance!
